<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-251-213  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 251 213.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Macworld  Feb 1989 v6 n2 p220(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Apple Scanner. (Hardware Review) (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Webster, Bruce.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Apple Computer's Apple Scanner is a low, narrow unit that iscompletely controlled from the Macintosh.andP;  Apple Scanner can scanseveral resolutions: 75, 100, 125, 150, 200 and 300 dpi.andP;  Itperforms multiple levels of scaling, from 24 to 400 percent(depending on resolution) and it accepts various settings forcontrast, brightness, threshold and gray map.andP;  Two softwarepackages are provided with the unit: AppleScan, a standaloneapplication providing full control over the unit; and HyperScan,similar to AppleScan but designed to operate under HyperCard.andO;Apple Scanner's drawbacks include: it supports to few graduationsof gray scale, contrast and gray maps, it requires more disk spacethat it actually needs, and it is not capable of resolutionssufficient for professional typesetting.andP;  Apple Scanner, priced at$1,799, requires a hard disk, 1MB of RAM and System 6.0 or laterversion.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (products).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Product:   Apple Scanner (Scanning device).andO;Topic:     ScanningEvaluation.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>